	directAnswerHtml={`<strong style="color: var(--color-ink);">If you are Catholic, the Father's Heart Bible™ is for you — written with deep respect for the faith you hold.</strong> You carry a rich heritage: the Trinity, the saving work of Christ, the Mass, and the very prayer Jesus taught — "Our Father, who art in heaven." Yet many devout Catholics relate to God mostly through duty, ritual, and a quiet sense of needing to earn or maintain His favor. The <a href="https://fathersheartbible.com/read" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">Father's Heart Bible™</a> is a fresh English translation you can read and <em>listen to</em> free — and it reveals God as a <em>Father</em> from beginning to end. Whether you searched "bible verses for Catholics," "God as Father," "assurance of God's love," or "saved by grace" — the heart of the answer is this: you do not have to earn what is already yours. Your Father runs to meet you.`}
	keyTakeaway={`You are not God's beloved because of what you earn, perform, or maintain — you are His beloved child by grace, fully accepted, the moment you come home to Him.`}
	painsHeading={`Catholics around the world`}
	painsIntroHtml={`More than a billion people call themselves Catholic, carrying a faith of extraordinary depth and devotion. And beneath that devotion, many sincere believers quietly long to know God not just as Lord and Judge, but as a near and tender Father. The numbers tell part of the story.`}
	painStats={[
		{ value: `1.39B`, label: `baptized Catholics worldwide — about 17.8% of the global population (Vatican / Annuario Pontificio, 2024)` },
		{ value: `52M`, label: `U.S. adults are Catholic — roughly 20% of the country (Pew Research, 2024)` },
		{ value: `29%`, label: `of U.S. Catholics say they attend Mass weekly or more (Pew Research, 2024)` },
		{ value: `28%`, label: `of U.S. Catholics report reading Scripture on their own at least monthly (Pew Research)` },
		{ value: `13M`, label: `U.S. adults raised Catholic now describe themselves as former Catholics (Pew Research)` },
		{ value: `53%`, label: `of U.S. Catholics say they pray daily — a longing for closeness with God (Pew Research)` },
	]}
	painsBodyHtml={`<p>Behind every number is a real person who loves God and wants to be close to Him. If you grew up Catholic, you may know the rhythms by heart — the Mass, the rosary, confession, the feast days, the prayers passed down through generations. There is real beauty in all of it. And yet many faithful Catholics carry a quieter ache: a sense that God is mostly distant, more watching than embracing; that His favor must be earned through enough devotion, kept through enough effort, and recovered through enough penance; that guilt is the steady background hum of faith, and assurance of His love feels just out of reach.</p><p>If that is you, please hear this gently: the longing you feel is holy. It is the very thing your own faith proclaims when you pray "Our Father." The God you already worship is a Father — and He is far nearer, far more tender, and far more delighted in you than fear and obligation have let you believe. The same Scripture the Church has treasured for two thousand years tells you so, on its own pages, in your own language.</p>`}
	painsSources={[
		{ label: `Pew Research — 10 Facts About U.S. Catholics`, url: `https://www.pewresearch.org/short-reads/2025/03/04/10-facts-about-us-catholics/` },
		{ label: `CARA — Center for Applied Research in the Apostolate, Georgetown University`, url: `https://cara.georgetown.edu/frequently-requested-church-statistics/` },
		{ label: `Vatican — Holy See Press Office (Church statistics)`, url: `https://press.vatican.va/content/salastampa/en.html` },
	]}
	aFatherHeading={`A Father for Catholics`}
	aFatherBodyHtml={`<p>Here is what your faith has been pointing you toward all along: the answer to the distance and the duty is not more effort, more penance, or a perfect record of devotion. The answer is a <strong style="color: var(--color-ink);">Father</strong> — the very Father you address every time you pray the prayer Jesus gave us.</p><p>You were not made to earn your way into God's favor. You were made to receive His love as a gift. Jesus told a story to show us the Father's heart: a son who had squandered everything came stumbling home rehearsing his apology — and while he was still a long way off, the father saw him, was filled with compassion, ran to him, and threw his arms around him. The son never finished earning his way back. The Father had already run.</p><p>That is who God is toward you. Not a distant overseer keeping score, but a Father watching the road for you — ready to run, to embrace, to call you His own. Your devotion is precious to Him. But it was never the price of His love. By grace, before you do a single thing, you are already His beloved child.</p>`}
